00:51:22.980 --> 00:51:26.380
So sometimes they are inaccurate.

00:51:26.380 --> 00:51:29.560
And then the other
thing is that sometimes

00:51:29.560 --> 00:51:33.330
within the individual
cylinder there will be sections

00:51:33.330 --> 00:51:36.550
where you can audibly hear
the cylinder coming up to

00:51:36.550 --> 00:51:39.130
that recording speed, so it will--

00:51:39.130 --> 00:51:42.630
it makes it like zipper
sound as it comes from a high

00:51:42.630 --> 00:51:44.150
to low frequency and levels out.

00:51:44.150 --> 00:51:49.500
So, there is some variation within
the individual cylinder about that.

00:51:49.500 --> 00:51:51.990
[ Inaudible Remark ]

00:51:51.990 --> 00:51:56.050
Yeah. There were a few
where there were many,

00:51:56.050 --> 00:51:57.900
many of those speed changes,

00:51:57.900 --> 00:52:01.850
but again that's like,
maybe five in 500.

00:52:07.430 --> 00:52:17.150
&gt;&gt; Did I understand correctly?

00:52:17.150 --> 00:52:36.870
Probably didn't which
is why I am asking.

00:52:36.870 --> 00:52:40.110
Was your digital image
output actually more accurate

00:52:40.110 --> 00:52:41.410
than the original recording?

00:52:41.410 --> 00:52:47.220
And if so could that be
corrected with something later

00:52:47.220 --> 00:52:51.590
down the road once all
of these are scanned

00:52:51.590 --> 00:52:54.120
with some type of 3D
printing device?

00:52:54.120 --> 00:52:58.640
&gt;&gt; Olivia Dill: So the question
was if our method is more accurate

00:52:58.640 --> 00:53:03.160
than the actual playback
of the cylinder and if

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:06.190
that could be corrected
with 3D printing.

00:53:06.190 --> 00:53:08.600
It's less a matter of accurate and
more a matter of-- I think you're--

00:53:08.600 --> 00:53:13.450
are you referring to the frequency
domain that I talked about?

00:53:13.450 --> 00:53:14.750
It's--

00:53:14.750 --> 00:53:16.920
&gt;&gt; If that makes sense,
that's what I'm referring to.

00:53:16.920 --> 00:53:21.570
&gt;&gt; Olivia Dill: So it
just ends up being that--

00:53:21.570 --> 00:53:26.170 position:56%
a playback stylus can only play back
up to a certain frequency of audio.

00:53:26.170 --> 00:53:30.060
And then after that frequency,
if there is anything there,

00:53:30.060 --> 00:53:31.890
it gets attenuated
and the volume drops.

00:53:31.890 --> 00:53:36.260
And that happens typically
around like 4000 hertz.

00:53:36.260 --> 00:53:41.880
And the recording capabilities
of the devices

00:53:41.880 --> 00:53:48.950
in the first place only
went up to about 5000 hertz.

00:53:48.950 --> 00:53:55.250
So there's that 1000 hertz sweet
spot where we're catching audio

00:54:00.300 --> 00:54:06.310
that can't be played
back with a stylus.

00:54:06.310 --> 00:54:18.800
So in that regard, we are
getting more information

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:23.600
than you can have by
playing them back.

00:54:23.600 --> 00:54:28.910
But in terms of if we are
creating information that's not

00:54:28.910 --> 00:54:35.300
in the cylinder, I-- my tendency
is to say that that's not the case.

00:54:35.300 --> 00:54:36.760
Yeah, I hope that helps.

