00:54:43.960 --> 00:54:46.510
with cylinders to reproduce
sounds, and will you be--

00:54:46.510 --> 00:54:49.680
is this technology can
be taken on the road,

00:54:49.680 --> 00:54:51.310
what's the adaptability
and scalability?

00:54:51.310 --> 00:54:52.610
&gt;&gt; Olivia Dill: OK.

00:54:52.610 --> 00:54:56.540
So the question was about how our
method compares to existing methods

00:54:56.540 --> 00:55:00.650
of transfer and if ours
is scalable and movable.

00:55:00.650 --> 00:55:02.370
So there are-- the other
I think common method

00:55:02.370 --> 00:55:04.430
of digitizing these
things is the archeophone.

00:55:04.430 --> 00:55:09.060
And so again, there is that
1000 or so hertz bandwidth

00:55:09.060 --> 00:55:15.250
of frequency range that we can
recover that that device cannot.

00:55:15.250 --> 00:55:23.310
It just ends up being a question
of whether or not there's anything

00:55:23.310 --> 00:55:24.610
that you want to recover.

00:55:24.610 --> 00:55:28.240
But the information
from our system up above

00:55:28.240 --> 00:55:31.790
in that high-frequency range,

00:55:31.790 --> 00:55:35.360
even if it's not recovering
vocal content,

00:55:35.360 --> 00:55:39.610
it is recovering the content that
allows us to do our blob cleaning

00:55:39.610 --> 00:55:41.900
and to see these high-frequency
effects.

00:55:41.900 --> 00:55:46.230 position:56%
So, that's kind of where our system
differs from those existing systems.

00:55:46.230 --> 00:55:51.250
And as far as transportability,
it's-- I mean once we built it,

00:55:51.250 --> 00:55:54.310
it's pretty much-- we could
take it apart and rebuild it

00:55:54.310 --> 00:55:56.920
and move it, it would be difficult.

00:55:56.920 --> 00:56:05.070
There's also a little bit of
particularity in where we place it.

00:56:05.070 --> 00:56:09.640
Currently, I work in a basement
and we like that because, again,

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:11.720
vibrations leach into system.

00:56:11.720 --> 00:56:14.720
And so if you're up on the
sixth floor of a building--

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:34.310
we do have another version of
this that's up on the sixth floor

00:56:35.510 --> 00:56:39.700
of a building-- and the
building itself wobbles,

00:56:39.700 --> 00:56:42.560
and so that's something
that they have to account

00:56:42.560 --> 00:56:45.480
for in their measurements.

00:56:45.480 --> 00:56:51.110
So, there's that factor
about where you put it.

00:56:51.110 --> 00:56:56.860
It is difficult and it does require
precision to build and to maintain,

00:56:56.860 --> 00:57:00.000
so there's that sort of
skill set investment as well.

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:02.580
But in scalability,
I think this is--

00:57:02.580 --> 00:57:07.210
that's kind of what we're trying
to figure out in this process is

00:57:07.210 --> 00:57:11.370
if we can scale it to make it
larger and make it more applicable

00:57:11.370 --> 00:57:12.860
for production and
systematic scanning.

00:57:12.860 --> 00:57:14.160
Does that help?

00:57:14.160 --> 00:57:15.690
&gt;&gt; I'm just curious how
you do the image stitching

00:57:15.690 --> 00:57:18.060
with the different
[inaudible] section

00:57:18.060 --> 00:57:20.020
and like how much overlap you have
to have between two adjacent spots

00:57:20.020 --> 00:57:21.320
to get like an accurate
idea of how to [inaudible].

00:57:21.320 --> 00:57:22.620
&gt;&gt; Olivia Dill: Yeah, so--
that's actually interesting.

00:57:22.620 --> 00:57:23.920
The question was about stitching

00:57:23.920 --> 00:57:25.220
and how we compile--
separate scans, correct?

00:57:25.220 --> 00:57:26.520
So, it typically takes about four
millimeters of overlap is my cutoff

00:57:26.520 --> 00:57:27.820
between the first and
the second image.

00:57:27.820 --> 00:57:29.120
And the interesting thing
is we don't actually do

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:30.420
that stitching together
visually with the image,

00:57:30.420 --> 00:57:31.720
we produce two separate audio files

00:57:31.720 --> 00:57:33.020
and then we use commercial
audio processing software

00:57:33.020 --> 00:57:34.320
to find the identical point
between those audio files

00:57:34.320 --> 00:57:35.620
and then we basically just cut
and paste and stick them together.

00:57:35.620 --> 00:57:36.920 position:56%
And it's kind of a comfort that they
usually end up being identical even

00:57:36.920 --> 00:57:38.220
if the scan is done
a little bit later.

00:57:38.220 --> 00:57:39.520
There is at some point in the audio

00:57:39.520 --> 00:57:40.820
from both sections that's visibly
identical at the waveform level.

00:57:40.820 --> 00:57:42.160 position:56%
&gt;&gt; What's maximum length of time in
