00:57:56.760 --> 00:58:00.690
and that was a very high resolution
and very high exposure time,

00:58:00.690 --> 00:58:03.860
but that's way beyond
sort of the threshold

00:58:03.860 --> 00:58:06.370
and I've seen broken cylinders

00:58:06.370 --> 00:58:12.230 position:56%
that the scanning process took
maybe an hour but the actual process

00:58:12.230 --> 00:58:14.820
of me trying to physically
manipulate it and get it

00:58:14.820 --> 00:58:19.490
to stay still while it was
being measured took eight hours.

00:58:19.490 --> 00:58:22.760
But that's probably my
fault not the software's.

00:58:23.900 --> 00:58:33.410
&gt;&gt; More from an aesthetic
standpoint,

00:58:34.430 --> 00:58:41.060
since this was before the time

00:58:41.060 --> 00:58:44.130
when recording engineers
was really even a thing.

00:58:44.130 --> 00:58:48.440
Do you find a lot of variability in
the quality of the recordings or,

00:58:48.440 --> 00:58:49.770
like, you know, the audibility?

00:58:49.770 --> 00:58:53.160
&gt;&gt; Olivia Dill: So the
question was about variability

00:58:53.160 --> 00:58:54.700
and differences in quality.

00:58:54.700 --> 00:58:56.000
It does vary a lot.

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:59.810
A big factor is how well the
cylinder has been preserved,

00:58:59.810 --> 00:59:01.110
the cylinder that's had a lot

00:59:01.110 --> 00:59:03.670
of mold damage sounds
are very, very bad.

00:59:03.670 --> 00:59:08.210
So that's kind of the biggest
most immediate factor for me

00:59:08.210 --> 00:59:09.990
as somebody listening back.

00:59:09.990 --> 00:59:12.230
But in terms of what
was originally there,

00:59:12.230 --> 00:59:15.480
there is a lot of variability.

00:59:15.480 --> 00:59:18.570
Something that we see a lot is,

00:59:18.570 --> 00:59:24.980
if the audio that's being
recorded is too loud then we see--

00:59:24.980 --> 00:59:27.910
the stylus needs to
trace out a very steep

00:59:27.910 --> 00:59:32.450
and very tall vertical oscillation,
and sometimes the height

00:59:32.450 --> 00:59:36.220
of that oscillation is higher
than the surface of the cylinder,

00:59:36.220 --> 00:59:38.630
so you see that the needle pops
out the top of the cylinder

00:59:38.630 --> 00:59:41.660
to every upswing and then
comes back down sometime later

00:59:41.660 --> 00:59:43.010
and that's called clipping.

00:59:43.010 --> 00:59:49.380
And so that's a big, very clearly
ineffective how the cylinder was

00:59:49.380 --> 00:59:51.350
recorded, how close the
person was to the horn,

00:59:51.350 --> 00:59:54.670
how loud they were speaking
and if they've been instructed

00:59:54.670 --> 00:59:57.450
to record properly,
so we see that a lot.

00:59:57.450 --> 01:00:01.870
And that's the biggest thing I
have noticed, is just volume,

01:00:01.870 --> 01:00:04.040
how clear they're speaking.

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:07.140
If the stylus-- Again, sometimes
you see these recording anomalies

01:00:07.140 --> 01:00:10.400
where it's clear but something
was off in the recording.

01:00:10.400 --> 01:00:14.450
Something was broken or somebody
wasn't handling it carefully,

01:00:14.450 --> 01:00:18.310
so that will affect your output.

01:00:18.310 --> 01:00:20.160
Yeah, that's about all I've seen.

01:00:20.160 --> 01:00:48.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; For those who may be new to
